{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489645","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489645"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:24:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:24:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"708"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"708","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/708"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.77,0.12,0.07,0.02,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"708"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76739"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"708","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/708"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"708"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62232"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"379"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"8850"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5744"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5879"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76739","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76739"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 27-year-old man is being reviewed after a recent blow to the head. He complained of some initial dizziness, but that has now settled. A cranial nerve examination is performed and the patient is asked to look directly ahead (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following cranial nerves has been affected?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Right third nerve palsy","Left third nerve palsy","Right fourth nerve palsy","Left fourth nerve palsy","Left sixth nerve palsy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPalsy of the \u003Cstrong\u003Ethird cranial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E (oculomotor nerve) results in a characteristic \u0027down and out\u0027 gaze when the patient is asked to look straight ahead. It is also associated with partial ptosis and pupillary dilation. The third cranial nerve ipsilaterally innervates specific extra-ocular muscles and the levator palpebrae superioris. Only the patient\u0027s right eye is affected and this allows localisation of the \u003Cstrong\u003Ecranial nerve palsy to the right third nerve\u003C/strong\u003E, as opposed to the \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft third nerve\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe specific extra-ocular muscles innervated by the third cranial nerve are the medial rectus, superior rectus, inferior rectus, and inferior oblique. When these muscles are weakened in a third nerve palsy, the unopposed lateral rectus and superior oblique muscles pull the eye into the down and out position. Partial ptosis occurs due to weakness of the levator palpebrae superioris as it normally functions to retract the upper eyelid. Pupillary dilatation in the affected eye occurs due to impaired parasympathetic input from the third nerve to the sphincter pupillae muscle. Pupillary dilation does not always occur in a third nerve palsy, often being spared in ischaemic causes. In an isolated acute third nerve palsy with pupillary dilation - an aneurysm of the posterior communicating artery must be ruled out immediately.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf there were a \u003Cstrong\u003Efourth nerve\u003C/strong\u003E (trochlear nerve) palsy - the characteristic appearance is a subtle upward deviation of the affected eye and/or a compensatory head turn away from the affected side. This occurs due to weakness of the superior oblique muscle which is innervated by the fourth nerve.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Esixth nerve\u003C/strong\u003E (abducens nerve) palsy would present as an inward turned eye with an inability to abduct the eye on the affected side. This inwards turn of the eye occurs due to weakness of the lateral rectus muscle in the setting of unopposed action of the adductors of the eye (mainly the medial rectus).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cranial nerve III (oculomotor) innervates the medial rectus, superior rectus, inferior rectus, and inferior oblique.","Palsy of cranial nerve III (oculomotor) results in a down and out gaze due to unopposed action of the lateral rectus and superior oblique with associated partial ptosis and pupillary dilation.","In an acute isolated third nerve palsy with pupillary dilatation - an aneurysm of the posterior communicating artery must be ruled out immediately."],"references":["Duncan, Jacque L., et al. \u0022Cranial Nerve Palsies.\u0022 Current Medical Diagnosis \u0026 Treatment 2022 Eds. Maxine A. Papadakis, et al. McGraw Hill, 2022.","Modi P, Arsiwalla T. Cranial Nerve III Palsy. 2023 Jul 4. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30252368.","Yanovitch T, Buckley E. Diagnosis and management of third nerve palsy. Curr Opin Ophthalmol. 2007 Sep;18(5):373-8. doi: 10.1097/ICU.0b013e328270b8db. PMID: 17700229."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62232"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"708"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14831"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14831","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14831"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/767cf058-8acd-4761-b7be-b8edc0a38841.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/767cf058-8acd-4761-b7be-b8edc0a38841.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":477,"height":314}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"